posts.name: Owen Busler
posts.cooked: Howdy yall, we are looking at having 2 analog distance sensors on the end of our elevator to know when we have acquired a coral. To get CAN up our elevator, and the voltage/signal to each of the sensors, can we use the individual wires in an UNSHIELDED ethernet? My question is both is this legal (im pretty sure it is) and do you think that the unshielded ethernet running with power for 2 motor controllers up a cable chain will cause crosstalk/interference issues? Would shielded twisted pair help?

posts.name: Jeffrey Morris
posts.cooked:
For sensor power and CAN , yes twisted-pair ethernet works great and our CANnect product works using them.

I am confused however, do you mean you want to run analog signals through it as well, or do they also work over CAN ? Your analog signals are going to be much more susceptible to interferance than CAN and I would frown upon running analog wires so far (it very well could work fine but I feel you may run into issues).

posts.name: Owen Busler
posts.cooked:
Yeah we were going to have these 8 wires

Can H Can L 5v (Sensor power) Ground (Sensor Ground) Sensor 1 Analog Value Sensor 2 Analog Value Spare Spare

The analog wires were the ones I was also worried about, do you think shielded ethernet would help?

posts.name: Jeffrey Morris
posts.cooked:
Ok I understand now.

To be honest, Im not entirely sure how your analog signals will fare going such distances and being bombarded with so much interferance.

I would assume that your best bet would be to put one analog and one usused per twisted-pair and use shielded cables (even better to connect the shield to ground)

So: Pair 1: CAN H & CAN L Pair 2: PWR & GND Pair 3: Analog 1 & unused Pair 4: Analog 2 & unused

Make sure you check R622 for power legality.

This is definitely a go-forth and do science situation and find out if it works!

posts.name: Owen Busler
posts.cooked: Thanks! We will amazon some shielded twisted pair and report how it goes! If it doesn’t work we will get a CAN distance sensor and swap them out.

posts.name: Jeffrey Morris
posts.cooked: Actually: for your analog pairs, pair them with ground.

posts.name: Owen Busler
posts.cooked:
Pair 1: CAN H & CAN L Pair 2: PWR & GND Pair 3: Analog 1 & GND Pair 4: Analog 2 & GND

Makes sense to me!

posts.name: philso
posts.cooked:
The 4 pairs of wires in an ethernet cable should be twisted together. Twisting pairs or wires together greatly increases the immunity to external noise sources.

While, you may have the power wiring for a couple of motor controllers in the same wiring bundle, the twisted pair should give you sufficient noise immunity, without shielding. I have used similar wiring in motor controllers that run at 10x to 1000x the power levels found in an FRC robot. Of course, you should test to make sure that the signals are not being corrupted in your exact application.

Please check any ethernet cables you are using to confirm whether or not they are really shielded since they typically are not shielded. The reviews of the one linked contains a photo showing that there is no shield over the cable.

Edit: I forgot to ask if the analog signals are connected to the Roborio. If they are, your programmers should add some code to do some filtering or averaging to further reduce noise effects. They should be careful doing this to ensure the response is not slowed too much.

You can also add a small capacitor from the signal pin to the GND pin at the Roborio to reduce any noise. Capacitors in the range of 1-100 nF are likely to be what you would want. Again you will have to test to make sure the capacitor does not slow down the response to the signal too much.

posts.name: SLAB-Mr.Thomas
posts.cooked:
My team has used the motor controller input for analog signals. If you want to run a circuit from the sensor to the roboRIO, test the wiring before making the effort to install it permanently. Depends on the sensor but 3’ to 4’ total length is about the max for most analog sensors we have used.

I can’t remember the details but IIRC there was something about selecting 3.3v or 5v or which breakout board to use to power the sensor from the motor controller. Maybe what I’m thinking of is scaling the signal for 3.3v or 5v range.
